Addition methods for classfication - Project related¶

  1. Logistic regression (Linear models)

  2. Lasso/Ridge regression (linear models with regulization)

  3. Nerual network ( Nonlinear models)

  4. KNN

  5. ...

Example: In 'mlbench' package, there is 'Sonar' data. The goal is to classify sonar signals as either rock (R) or mine (M) based on energy patterns returned by sonar pulses.

Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository.¶

Please build predictive models using different methods.

In [2]:
#Split the data into train set and test set
set.seed(252)

index = createDataPartition(Sonar$Class, p = 0.75, list = FALSE)
train.dat = Sonar[index,]
test.dat =   Sonar[-index,]

Loading required package: ggplot2

Loading required package: lattice
In [6]:
# Logistic regression with train function  (Issues: #Sonar dataset is high-dimensional relative to the sample size)

glm.fit = train(
  Class ~ ., data = train.dat,
  trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5),
  method = "glm",                
  family = "binomial"            #logistic regression
)

#Sonar dataset is high-dimensional relative to the sample size

#Lasso and elasticnet
#glmnet

#Option: data scaling

#Lasso  ,  alpha = 1
#The tuning parameter  controls the overall strength of the penalty.
#family="gaussian"   == > lm
lambda.value = 0.5


#Prepare data matrices for glmnet
X.train <- as.matrix(train.dat[, 1:60])
X.test  <- as.matrix(test.dat[, 1:60])

# Response: convert factor to numeric 0/1 (M = 1, R = 0)
y.train <- ifelse(train.dat$Class == "M", 1, 0)
y.test  <- ifelse(test.dat$Class == "M", 1, 0)


# lambda = 0.5 (example fixed value)
#LASSO logistic regression (alpha = 1)
lambda.value <- 0.5
lasso.fit <- glmnet(
  X.train, y.train,
  family = "binomial",
  alpha = 1,
  lambda = lambda.value
)

# Predicted probabilities on the test set
pred.prob <- predict(lasso.fit, newx = X.test, type = "response")

# threshold = 0.5
pred.class <- ifelse(pred.prob >= 0.5, "M", "R")
pred.class <- factor(pred.class, levels = c("R", "M"))

confusionMatrix(pred.class, test.dat$Class)

roc.obj <- roc(y.test, as.vector(pred.prob))
auc <- auc(roc.obj)
auc

# Plot ROC curve
plot(
  roc.obj,
  col = "blue",
  lwd = 2,
  main = "ROC Curve - LASSO Logistic Regression"
)
legend("bottomright", legend = paste("AUC =", round(auc_value, 3)), bty = "n")

Chapter 12: Logistic Regression¶

Classification problems are similar to regression problems, with the key distinction that the response variable takes on only a small number of discrete categories. We begin with binary classification, where the response variable $Y$ takes values $0$ or $1$. (Most concepts discussed here extend naturally to multi-class classification.)

Let $$ p(x) = P(Y = 1 \mid X = x) $$ denote the probability that the outcome equals 1, given the predictors $X = (X_1, \ldots, X_p)$.

Logistic Regression Model¶

Logistic regression models the log-odds (logit) of $Y = 1$ as a linear function of the predictors:

$$ \log\left( \frac{p(x)}{1 - p(x)} \right) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p. $$

The odds are defined as $$ \text{odds} = \frac{p(x)}{1 - p(x)}. $$

Exponentiating both sides gives $$ \frac{p(x)}{1 - p(x)} = \exp(\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p), $$ and solving for $p(x)$ yields the logistic (sigmoid) function:

$$ p(x) = \frac{\exp(\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p)} {1 + \exp(\beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \cdots + \beta_p X_p)}. $$

Classification Thresholds¶

A logistic regression model outputs a probability $\hat{p}(x)$ for class 1. To convert this probability into a class label, we apply a threshold:

  • Predict class 1 if $\hat{p}(x) \ge \tau$
  • Predict class 0 if $\hat{p}(x) < \tau$

The standard choice is $\tau = 0.5$, but the optimal threshold often differs in applications such as:

  • Medical diagnosis
  • Risk assessment
  • Fraud detection

The threshold affects sensitivity and specificity and can be tuned using ROC curves or cost-based criteria.

Logistic Regression Using caret in R¶

library(caret)

default_glm_mod <- train(
  form = default ~ .,
  data = default_trn,
  trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5),
  method = "glm",
  family = "binomial"
)

# View cross-validated results
default_glm_mod$results

# View the fitted model
default_glm_mod$finalModel
